# Never Silently Ignore Errors

Every returned `error` / `CategorizedError` must be handled — returned,
logged, or explicitly acted on. Do not drop errors on the floor.

See also [server-error-handling.mdc](server-error-handling.mdc) for which
error *category* to return.

## Forbidden

- `_ = doThing()` or `x, _ := doThing()` — discarding the error.
- `if err == nil { use(x) }` with no `else` — the failure path silently
  vanishes: the value is consumed on success but a real error is lost.
- Swallowing with no rationale (empty block, bare `//nolint`).

```go
// Bad — error silently dropped.
timerID, _ := ids.ParseTaskID(s)

// Bad — failure path vanishes; a corrupt s is silently skipped.
if id, err := ids.ParseTaskID(s); err == nil {
    md.TimerTaskCommittedID = id
}
```

## If you genuinely must ignore an error

1. Leave a code comment explaining WHY it is safe to ignore.
2. Call it out in the PR description / review so a human signs off.

```go
// OK — explicit, with rationale.
// Close is best-effort on shutdown; a failure changes nothing here.
_ = conn.Close()
```

## Prefer fail-fast over silent ignore for "impossible" errors

If an error is effectively unreachable because the value comes from a
TRUSTED source (our own store rows, server-generated ids), use a `Must*`
helper that panics instead of silently ignoring it. A violated invariant
is a bug to surface, not swallow.

```go
// Trusted DB value: a non-UUID here means data corruption → fail fast.
md.TimerTaskCommittedID = ids.MustParseTaskID(s)
```

Even better: thread the typed value end-to-end so there is no parse (and
no error branch) at all — that is why `ids.TaskID` flows through the
task pipeline instead of `string`.

## Never panic on UNTRUSTED input

Client/wire-supplied values must be handled defensively (drop, default,
or return `InvalidInputError`) — never `Must*`/panic. A malicious client
must not be able to crash the server.

```go
// Untrusted inbound RPC: a client that maliciously sends the server-internal
// EncodedObjectBlobIdInternalOnly variant is neutralized to Null here — never
// trusted, never parsed-and-panicked-on.
func pbValueToPersistence(pbVal *pb.Value, blobID ids.BlobID) p.Value {
    switch v := pbVal.Kind.(type) {
    case *pb.Value_EncodedObjectBlobIdInternalOnly:
        return p.Value{Type: p.ValueTypeNull} // drop, don't trust
    ...
    }
}
```

### Validating a client-supplied id

If a future RPC accepts an id string FROM a client, validate it with the
error-returning `ids.Validate*` helper (e.g. `ids.ValidateBlobID`) and wrap
the failure as `InvalidInputError` — do NOT reach for `ids.MustParse*`
(panic). `ids` exposes `MustParse*` for trusted store reads and `Validate*`
for untrusted input; pick by the value's source.

```go
// Good — untrusted client id: validate, return InvalidInputError, never panic.
blobID, err := ids.ValidateBlobID(req.BlobId)
if err != nil {
    return nil, errors.NewInvalidInputError("invalid blob_id", err)
}
```

## Trusted vs untrusted — the deciding question

Ask where the value came from, not what type it is. The SAME field can be
both: an `EncodedObjectBlobIdInternalOnly` is **untrusted** on an inbound RPC
(dropped by `pbValueToPersistence`) but **trusted** when later read back from
our own history store (hydrated with `MustParseBlobID`).

- **Trusted** → `Must*` / panic acceptable: our own DB rows, ids we minted
  server-side, invariants we control.
- **Untrusted** → must handle gracefully: gRPC request fields, SDK/worker
  payloads, anything a client can set — including proto fields named
  "internal only".

## Review checklist

Reject:

- A discarded error (`_ =` / `, _ :=`) with no explaining comment.
- An `if err == nil { ... }` that has no `else` handling the error.
- A `Must*`/panic reached from client- or wire-supplied input.
